## What Is the Difference Between AI Search Optimisation and Generative Engine Optimisation?

GEO and AI search optimisation are often used interchangeably — this service covers both. GEO focuses specifically on optimising for generative AI responses, whilst AI search optimisation encompasses the broader strategy of appearing across all AI-powered search interfaces.

Traditional SEO and GEO share foundational principles — quality content, clear structure, demonstrable expertise. Their optimisation targets differ. **Traditional SEO** optimises for ranking signals: backlinks, keyword relevance, and technical performance. **GEO** optimises for citation signals: factual precision, source credibility, answer completeness, and structured formatting. A site can hold position 1 in traditional results and never appear in an AI answer. A site at position 8 can become the primary cited source — content quality and answer directness determine citation selection, not ranking position alone.

The distinction matters because AI search includes platforms that blend traditional ranking with AI-generated summaries (Google AI Overviews, Bing Copilot) alongside pure generative engines (ChatGPT, Perplexity). A comprehensive AI search optimisation strategy addresses both categories, ensuring visibility whether users encounter AI-enhanced traditional search or dedicated AI research tools.

My guide on [what LLM optimisation involves](/blog/what-is-llm-optimisation/) explores the technical foundations of how large language models select, process, and cite source material. Understanding these mechanics informs practical optimisation decisions across all AI search platforms.

## How Do You Measure AI Search Optimisation Success?

Measuring AI search performance requires expanding beyond traditional SEO metrics because many AI interactions don't generate direct website visits. Effective measurement combines several approaches.

**AI citation tracking** monitors when and where your content appears in AI-generated responses. Tools are emerging that track brand mentions across ChatGPT, Perplexity, and other platforms, providing visibility into citation frequency and context.

**Bing Webmaster Tools AI data** already provides AI citation metrics for Bing Copilot, showing how frequently your pages are cited in AI-generated responses versus traditional organic results.

**Branded search volume changes** indicate whether AI citations are driving awareness. Increases in branded search queries after AI citation campaigns suggest users are discovering your brand through AI responses and seeking you out directly.

**Referral traffic from AI platforms** tracks direct visits from ChatGPT, Perplexity, and other AI engines that include clickable source links in their responses.

**Ranking correlation analysis** compares organic ranking changes with AI citation patterns, identifying content that performs well in both channels and content that requires channel-specific optimisation.

Understanding [how long SEO takes](/blog/how-long-does-seo-take/) applies equally to AI search optimisation. Building the topical authority and entity recognition that AI engines reward requires consistent effort over months, not overnight shortcuts.

